criticism[edit],"the us congressional budget office (cbo, 2009) examined the potential effects of the american clean energy and security act on us households.[81] this act relies heavily on the free allocation of permits. the bill was found to protect low-income consumers, but it was recommended that the bill be made more efficient by reducing welfare provisions for corporations, and that more resources be made available for consumer relief.  a cap-and-trade initiative in the u.s. northeast caused concerns it would be regressive and poorer households would absorb most of the new tax.[82]
